WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:03.700
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:05.450 --> 00:00:06.450


00:00:06.760 --> 00:00:09.226
&gt;&gt; Good morning and
happy anniversary.

00:00:13.080 --> 00:00:14.546
This is the 10th year.

00:00:15.580 --> 00:00:16.580
[ Applause ]

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:22.433
&gt;&gt; The 10th year of the National
Book Festival and it is people

00:00:23.940 --> 00:00:28.673
like you, book lovers and people who
love to come and meet authors who--

00:00:30.190 --> 00:00:32.123
and aren't afraid to show it,

00:00:32.190 --> 00:00:34.856
who make this great
institution possible.

00:00:36.660 --> 00:00:36.790
Before we begin, I
want to inform you

00:00:38.930 --> 00:00:39.113
that the pavilion's presentations
are being filmed for the Library

00:00:43.080 --> 00:00:43.450
of Congress, for the website
and for their archives.

00:00:46.110 --> 00:00:48.576
So, if you step up
and ask a question,

00:00:48.900 --> 00:00:50.900
you are going down in history.

00:00:50.900 --> 00:00:51.343
I want you to be aware
of that [laughter].

00:00:53.190 --> 00:00:55.856
And please don't sit
on the camera risers

00:00:56.110 --> 00:00:56.443
and turn off your cellphones
if you would.

00:00:58.510 --> 00:00:59.510
Thank you.

00:01:00.510 --> 00:01:01.643
I am Marie Arana.

00:01:02.510 --> 00:01:04.376
I am a writer at large for The
Washington Post and I'm here

00:01:04.510 --> 00:01:07.376
to introduce your host,
Dr. James Billington

00:01:07.570 --> 00:01:07.970
who has been the United
States Librarian of Congress

00:01:10.570 --> 00:01:12.970
for 23 marvelously productive years.

00:01:13.510 --> 00:01:14.510
[ Applause ]

00:01:22.080 --> 00:01:25.346
&gt;&gt; He is only the 13th
person to hold the position

00:01:25.470 --> 00:01:28.603
since the library was
established 210 years ago.

00:01:29.700 --> 00:01:30.833
Think about that.

00:01:31.700 --> 00:01:31.846
There have been 43 presidents
from John Adams to Barrack Obama

00:01:35.620 --> 00:01:38.086
but there have only
been 13 librarians

00:01:38.230 --> 00:01:40.163
of Congress during that time.

00:01:40.700 --> 00:01:44.500
Dr. Billington's accomplishments
are legend and legendary.

00:01:44.700 --> 00:01:46.433
Allow me to mention a few.

00:01:46.700 --> 00:01:47.643
He is the force behind the Librarian
National Digital Library Program

00:01:50.290 --> 00:01:53.623
which makes available
online, millions and millions

00:01:53.870 --> 00:01:54.380
of publications from the
Library of Congress as well

00:01:56.760 --> 00:01:57.120
as from other libraries and research
institutions around the globe.

00:02:00.800 --> 00:02:01.270
He created the James Madison
Council whose members helped govern

00:02:04.530 --> 00:02:04.643
and shape the important
work that the library does.

00:02:07.750 --> 00:02:08.000
He is the founder of the John W.
Kluge Center, a haven for scholars

00:02:11.900 --> 00:02:14.633
around the world who
produce a wider array

00:02:14.820 --> 00:02:16.886
of ground-breaking scholarship.

00:02:16.950 --> 00:02:16.963
He's established unprecedented
exchange programs with Russia

00:02:20.870 --> 00:02:21.050
which is in fact, his
personal field of scholarship.

00:02:24.090 --> 00:02:28.490
But in truth, he's built bridges
with regions all around the world.

00:02:28.970 --> 00:02:29.766
Perhaps, most important at least
today on the 10th anniversary

00:02:32.240 --> 00:02:34.773
of this magnificent
living institution,

00:02:35.110 --> 00:02:35.413
Dr. Billington is the mastermind
behind the National Book Festival

00:02:39.140 --> 00:02:42.873
along with Laura Bush and this
festival as you well know,

00:02:43.770 --> 00:02:46.703
is one the great public
celebrations of books

00:02:47.070 --> 00:02:48.936
and reading in this country.

00:02:49.070 --> 00:02:52.470
It's a great honor to
introduce a national treasure,

00:02:52.990 --> 00:02:54.503
the director of the National Book
Festival and the US Librarian

00:02:55.610 --> 00:02:57.876
of Congress, Dr. James Billington.

00:02:58.110 --> 00:02:59.110
[ Applause ]

00:03:11.600 --> 00:03:12.266
&gt;&gt; Thank you very much
Marie and welcome.

00:03:13.600 --> 00:03:17.666
Welcome to you all for this 10th
Annual National Book Festival

00:03:19.110 --> 00:03:23.176
for our opening ceremonies and
this is a milestone anniversary

00:03:24.590 --> 00:03:24.710
of what we have been calling a
decade of words and wonder dedicated

00:03:28.870 --> 00:03:33.003
to the celebration of books,
reading to literacy and libraries,

00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:37.946
and above all, to the wonderful
experience of one author speaking

00:03:38.510 --> 00:03:41.310
to one individual,
individuals of all ages.

00:03:41.740 --> 00:03:42.043
We thank you for being here and let
me just say a word of special thanks

00:03:46.170 --> 00:03:47.703
to Marie Arana who does

00:03:49.090 --> 00:03:49.523
such a wonderful special
job of introducing--

00:03:51.590 --> 00:03:52.590
[ Applause ]

00:03:58.360 --> 00:04:03.026
&gt;&gt; Supported by our honorary chairs,
President Obama and Michelle Obama

00:04:03.070 --> 00:04:03.576
and organized by the
library, the wonderful staff,

00:04:05.830 --> 00:04:09.296
all these shirts you see
with National Book Festival,

00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:10.006
these are Library of Congress
volunteers of their own time.

00:04:12.740 --> 00:04:13.636
They're not getting overtime for
this but they want to be here

00:04:15.910 --> 00:04:15.920
because this is a corporate
expression of your library,

00:04:19.500 --> 00:04:22.766
The National Library, a
commitment to all of these

00:04:23.650 --> 00:04:25.316
and libraries everywhere.

00:04:25.650 --> 00:04:27.450
As we bring up the curtain.

00:04:28.150 --> 00:04:29.150
[ Applause ]

00:04:32.170 --> 00:04:32.910
&gt;. As we bring up the curtain
on this very happy occasion,

00:04:35.230 --> 00:04:35.470
we realize that there will be you
adults here in this very audience

00:04:39.390 --> 00:04:40.356
and throughout the day
who have virtually grown

00:04:41.490 --> 00:04:41.580
up with the National Books Festival.

00:04:43.800 --> 00:04:46.000
The offerings here are so varied.

00:04:46.170 --> 00:04:47.026
Our authors so diverse and skilled
that it's possible to come back year

00:04:49.980 --> 00:04:53.713
after a year, not only not
have the same experience twice

00:04:54.170 --> 00:04:57.770
but to find some new forum
of enrichment as well as fun

00:04:57.950 --> 00:05:01.083
because this is an
enjoyable festive atmosphere.

00:05:01.420 --> 00:05:04.753
It's a festival not a grim
duty and it's just great

00:05:05.070 --> 00:05:05.183
to see you all here on a clear day.

00:05:07.290 --> 00:05:07.486
We've welcomed so far over the
decade about a million book lovers

00:05:11.360 --> 00:05:15.026
of all ages to the National
Book Festival and this year,

00:05:15.430 --> 00:05:15.956
the festival has a
particularly international flavor.

00:05:18.370 --> 00:05:22.103
On our stages today, we have
several authors from variety

00:05:22.200 --> 00:05:22.526
of nations who've won prestigious
international awards including the

00:05:26.340 --> 00:05:30.273
Noble Prize for literature, we
welcome them all and we await

00:05:31.580 --> 00:05:31.623
to hear their stories
with great interest.

00:05:34.270 --> 00:05:37.603
Everybody loves a good
story, stories unify people,

00:05:38.340 --> 00:05:40.273
theories tend to divide them.

00:05:40.340 --> 00:05:40.783
America's a pretty great
story composed of a lot

00:05:43.030 --> 00:05:46.830
of individual stories and our
authors today span the globe

00:05:47.650 --> 00:05:49.383
as well as our own nation.

00:05:49.650 --> 00:05:53.716
So, it's a distinct privilege
to introduce our opening author,

00:05:54.050 --> 00:05:57.250
Isabel Allende who is
known throughout the world,

00:05:57.430 --> 00:06:00.163
is a best selling Chilean-American
writer,

00:06:00.380 --> 00:06:03.980
born in Lima where her father
was a Chilean Ambassador.

00:06:04.120 --> 00:06:04.790
Her uncle is Chilean
President, Salvador Allende,

00:06:06.650 --> 00:06:09.783
who was assassinated in
a military coup in 1973.

00:06:11.610 --> 00:06:15.743
Believing it unsafe to remain in
Chile, under those conditions,

00:06:16.170 --> 00:06:19.970
Isabel and her husband and two
children fled to Venezuela.

00:06:20.190 --> 00:06:21.156
While in exile, she wrote her first
novel, The House of the Spirits,

00:06:23.690 --> 00:06:26.023
which was made into a film in 1994.

00:06:27.050 --> 00:06:31.583
Her works weave wonderful elements
of that special quality of writers

00:06:33.080 --> 00:06:35.080
in our neighbors to the South.

00:06:35.440 --> 00:06:37.973
In this hemisphere,
the magical-realism

00:06:40.570 --> 00:06:44.503
which she's helped bring to us
and which often depicts women

00:06:46.130 --> 00:06:46.453
and their struggles with
particular sensitivity.

00:06:48.940 --> 00:06:49.336
She has written many
novels and other works,

00:06:51.410 --> 00:06:53.810
such as plays and children's
stories.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:58.466
Her most recent novel is The Island
Beneath the Sea, Harper Collins.

00:06:58.770 --> 00:07:01.236
Following this morning's
presentation,

00:07:02.320 --> 00:07:04.720
she will receive this year's Library

00:07:05.140 --> 00:07:09.206
of Congress National Book Festival
Creative Achievement Award.

00:07:09.960 --> 00:07:11.893
Sorry, that's a lot of words.

00:07:13.510 --> 00:07:14.510
[ Applause ]

00:07:23.430 --> 00:07:27.296
&gt;&gt; That's a lot of words but
she has such a universal range

00:07:27.300 --> 00:07:31.766
and such wonderful sense of humor
and humanity that we wouldn't work

00:07:32.380 --> 00:07:36.446
on reducing the name of that
prize in her honor to an acronym.

00:07:38.540 --> 00:07:38.680
Ladies and gentlemen, Isabel Allende
who will be interviewed this morning

00:07:43.200 --> 00:07:43.783
by author and Washington
Post writer Marie Arana

00:07:45.750 --> 00:07:49.083
and then she will be
followed by Dr. Deanna Marcum,

00:07:50.290 --> 00:07:54.890
the head of this year's Library of
Congress Team for the Book Festival

00:07:55.590 --> 00:07:59.723
who will present this special
non-acronym even if a little long

00:08:00.830 --> 00:08:04.763
in truth but short in wonderful
expression of direct feeling

00:08:07.590 --> 00:08:07.643
of gratitude for her giving
this international flavor.

00:08:11.070 --> 00:08:11.623
She is an American citizen who
we're very proud of and proud

00:08:14.450 --> 00:08:18.116
to give this award to and
once again, welcome to you all

00:08:18.500 --> 00:08:19.320
and welcome to your families,
your friends, and everyone else

00:08:21.680 --> 00:08:22.430
that can help make this
a really festive evening.

00:08:24.130 --> 00:08:24.396
Ladies and gentlemen, now, Marie--

00:08:26.130 --> 00:08:26.863
and no, one last word
[audience laughter].

00:08:28.130 --> 00:08:30.530
This is not just the
10th anniversary

00:08:30.840 --> 00:08:30.853
of what we've already
done but we have,

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:36.226
thanks to a very special
donor the assurance

00:08:37.030 --> 00:08:37.196
of another five years
not just next year.

00:08:39.530 --> 00:08:40.530
[ Applause ]

00:08:48.250 --> 00:08:51.516
&gt;&gt; So. So, please give a
special round of applause

00:08:51.860 --> 00:08:52.346
to our special donor, a great
friend of things in this city

00:08:55.240 --> 00:08:55.860
that are important to the country
as a whole, David Robinson.

00:08:58.620 --> 00:09:00.153
Please take a bow, sir.

00:09:01.120 --> 00:09:02.120
[ Applause ]

00:09:11.100 --> 00:09:12.833
&gt;&gt; And now, that wonderful

00:09:13.100 --> 00:09:16.366
and amazing spirit Marie
Arana and Isabel Allende.

00:09:17.420 --> 00:09:18.753
Thank you very much.

00:09:19.920 --> 00:09:20.920
[ Applause ]

